STEP 1 — Apex REST Class That Streams the Video Blob
@RestResource(urlMapping='/videoStream/*')
global with sharing class VideoStreamService {

    @HttpGet
    global static void streamVideo() {
        RestResponse res = RestContext.response;

        // Load the static resource as blob
        StaticResource sr = [
            SELECT Body, ContentType 
            FROM StaticResource 
            WHERE Name = 'MyVideoResource'  // <-- change to your SR name
            LIMIT 1
        ];

        res.addHeader('Content-Type', sr.ContentType);   // video/mp4
        res.addHeader('Cache-Control', 'max-age=3600');
        res.responseBody = sr.Body;                      // send blob
    }
}


This exposes a streaming endpoint:

/services/apexrest/videoStream

STEP 2 — Your LWC to Play the Video
videoPlayer.html
<template>
    <video controls width="600">
        <source src={videoUrl} type="video/mp4" />
        Your browser does not support the video tag.
    </video>
</template>

videoPlayer.js
import { LightningElement } from 'lwc';

export default class VideoPlayer extends LightningElement {
    videoUrl = '/services/apexrest/videoStream';
}

videoPlayer.js-meta.xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<LightningComponentBundle xmlns="http://soap.sforce.com/2006/04/metadata">
    <apiVersion>61.0</apiVersion>
    <isExposed>true</isExposed>
    <targets>
        <target>lightningCommunity__Page</target>
        <target>lightningCommunity__Default</target>
    </targets>
</LightningComponentBundle>

STEP 3 — Enable Guest User Access

You must allow the Experience Cloud Guest User to use the REST class.

Go to:

Setup → Sites → Your Experience Site → Public Access Settings

Under Enabled Apex Classes, add:

VideoStreamService

That’s it.

⭐ RESULT

Your LWC displays and plays the video correctly in Experience Cloud:

<video controls src="/services/apexrest/videoStream"></video>
